is comparable to cocaine, heroin, and cannabis.\",3\r\n1176,CEREBROSPINAL FLUID,\"Cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) is a clear fluid found in the brain and spinal cord, playing a crucial role in the central nervous system. It has been the subject of various studies due to its potential links to neurological and psychiatric conditions. Research has shown that levels of 5-hydroxyindoleacetic acid in CSF are associated with impulsive and aggressive behavior, highlighting its role in behavioral regulation. Additionally, CSF is studied for its involvement in glutamate function, particularly in patients with schizophrenia, suggesting its significance in understanding the neurochemical basis of this disorder. Together, these findings underscore the importance of cerebrospinal fluid in both behavioral and psychiatric research.\",2\r\n1184,HAFNER,\"Hafner is a researcher who studied the early symptoms of schizophrenia in Germany in 1992 and 1999, analyzing the onset and progression of the disease in patients\"\"\",2\r\n2336,MARK AND ERVIN,Mark and Ervin are researchers who studied the relationship between abnormal electrical activity in the limbic system and aggressive behavior in 1970.,2\r\n337,PINEL,\"Philippe Pinel was a pioneering French psychiatrist in the late 18th century who made significant contributions to the field of mental health. He is best known for his revolutionary approach to the treatment of mental illness, which included liberating patients from the chains and restraints that were commonly used in asylums at the time. Pinel transformed these institutions into more humane hospitals, emphasizing care and treatment over confinement and punishment. Additionally, he made important advancements in the classification of mental disorders, categorizing them into four distinct groups. His work laid the foundation for modern psychiatry and marked a turning point in the understanding and treatment of mental illness.\",3\r\n341,FRANCE,\"France is a country with a significant 